node.text:
I haven’t posted a YouTube video since college😅

Comment below anything you guys might want to see on my channel 🙏

The lil’ video editing work I did for insomniac recently brought back memories and reminded me just how much I love filming and editing (it just takes up a HELLA lot of time) and I’ve always wanted to vlog my raves, shoutout to @snewj, but knowing how crazy I get and how irresponsible I get with my belongings (learned my lesson after losing my phone and car keys at a festival) I didn’t trust myself carrying around my vlogging camera, much more having the attention span to vlog in the chaos of a rave. Soooo I just took hella ig stories instead and logged them on my highlights

It’s all good tho, since I love sharing the raw, real cringe af me with you guys... so I’m starting off my comeback with a new series named “the Uncensored Rave Vlogs” where I cleanup my highlights and move all my uncensored IG stories of me being stoopid from each rave to YouTube. Over time, these stories built up into a massive archive of the best moments of my life, traveling the country for the best times with some of the best people in one of my favorite cultures on the planet 🌎hope it provides some kind of entertainment or exposure to one of the most accepting cultures on the planet.

Here’s a small vid intro to my series with one of my favorite ncs songs from high school (full video and ig story highlights on youtube)

FOLLOW ME ON
Instagram: https://www.instagram.com/nylenayga
TikTok: @nylenayga
Facebook: https://www.facebook.com/nyle.nayga
Twitter: https://twitter.com/nylenayga
YouTube: https://www.youtube.com/nylenayga

node.title: aaaand WE’RE BACK ON YOUTUBE!  Dreamstate 2019

node.text:
I’m in a weird place right now.

If you’ve watched my stuff recently you might know life hit me like a f*cking truck.

I’m moving.
My best friend passed on to a better place.
My IG considered an “unsafe account” and may be “deleted”.
I’m cutting over half my coaching client space.
I’m creating my own fitness app.
I’m moving to YouTube. 
(But will still throw out epic vids here too)

And so much more with my state of health, relationships, some of which I can’t say…

I’ve never been in the middle of so many life-changing transitions at once in my entire life.

This twilight zone has truly taken it’s toll mentally and emotionally, but it’s hard times like these that test our faith, character, and determination to move forward… and not appreciating life and living it to the fullest would be an injustice to everything he stood for.

So I’ll come out.

Bigger.
Better.
Stronger.
And with the most epic videos you’ve seen me make yet.

Never give up baby. Stay tuned🤘

⚔️ 300 Shoulder Workout ⚔️
-
New EAA’s Mandarine Twist just DROPPED🍊🔥 Flavor is fire and the nootropics hit different forsure. My full workout supp stack is Pride, PSI, & OxyShred (stim/nonstim) for pre & EAA’s for intra. Supplements won’t replace nutrition and hard work - they’re just the tip of the iceberg - but every little bit can go a long way when you’re grinding for your all-time best 🏆🔝 
💠 Use code ‘NYLE10’ for 10% off 💠

Wearing @youngla • Perfecf Jogger Reatock 7/21 12pm pst
💠 Code ‘NYLE’ for 15% off 💠

1. Landmine Front Raise - 4 x 10-12
2. Barbell Overhead Press - 4 x 8-10
3. Dumbbell Arnold Press - 4 x 8-10
4. Leaning Kettlebell Lateral Raise - 5 x 15-16
5. Bent-Over Rear-Delt Raise - 4 x 15-16
6. Seated Thumbs-Down Mid-Rear Lateral Raise - 4 x 15-16
Notes:
2-3min rests between same exercises. One very light warm-up set each exercise before the sets above. Work up to heaviest weight by 2nd set. About (beginner: 2-4 reps/advanced: 1-2 reps) from failure each set. Final set of 5, 6, 7 to failure.
-
💪 ***www.nylenayga.com*** (in my bio)
Visit to explore my 1-on-1 COACHING Services, Personalized Bodybuilding PROGRAMS, or become a personal client @naygagains 👈👈
-
❗️My workouts tend to be more volume than optimal for beginner lifters. I make these routines for the purpose of building aesthetics based on the knowledge I’ve gained over the years in what workout splits and exercises I used to build and shape my own body. Each workout is provided with the intention of being a new routine for you in case you’ve hit a pleateau in progress with your current routine. 
In the end, progressive overload is what will drive hypertrophy (muscle gain), and the best way to actively measure progressive overload “accurately” is to measure the total volume of work done on that muscle group(s) and increase that volume by a small increment at each proceeding recurrence of that muscle group throughout your program. 

The easiest way to ensure you’re increasing volume is by keeping the exercises of each recurrence of that muscle group a constant

Chest & Triceps (High-Rep)
-
Wearing @youngla • Restock 7/21 12pm pst
💠 Code ‘NYLE’ for 15% off 💠

1. Incline Dumbbell Press - 4 x 10-12
2. Incline Squeeze Press - 3 x 12-14
3. Incline Underhand Dumbbell Fly - 4 x 15-16
4. Dip Machine (Hoist) - 4 x 15-16
5. Wide Lower-Chest Cable Fly - 4 x 15-16
6. Wide Upper-Chest Overhand Cable Fly - 4 x 15-16
7. Single-Arm Rope Overhead Tricep Extension - 5 x 16-18
Notes:
Finish with Incline Squeeze Press to failure. Rest in order. 2-3min rests between same exercises. One very light warm-up set each exercise before the sets above. Work up to heaviest weight by 2nd set. About (beginner: 2-4 reps/advanced: 1-2 reps) from failure each set. Final set of 5, 6, 7 to failure.
-
🧬I take @ehplabs Pride, OxyShred Non-Stim, & PSI for pre-workout • Use ‘NYLE10’ for 10% OFF
-
💪 ***www.nylenayga.com*** (in my bio)
Visit to explore my 1-on-1 COACHING Services, Personalized Bodybuilding PROGRAMS, or become a personal client @naygagains 👈👈
-
❗️My workouts tend to be more volume than optimal for beginner lifters. I make these routines for the purpose of building aesthetics based on the knowledge I’ve gained over the years in what workout splits and exercises I used to build and shape my own body. Each workout is provided with the intention of being a new routine for you in case you’ve hit a pleateau in progress with your current routine. 
In the end, progressive overload is what will drive hypertrophy (muscle gain), and the best way to actively measure progressive overload “accurately” is to measure the total volume of work done on that muscle group(s) and increase that volume by a small increment at each proceeding recurrence of that muscle group throughout your program. 

The easiest way to ensure you’re increasing volume is by keeping the exercises of each recurrence of that muscle group a constant (doing the same exercises at each recurrence) in order to eliminate exercise variance as a variable that could affect total volume of work done on that muscle group just by the nature of engaging in different exercises.
